File:  AFP/Thomas Kienzle JOHANNESBURG - A supplier who over-charged the South African Police Service for face masks has been slapped with R3.5 million fine by the Competition Tribunal. Tsutsumani Business Enterprises was found to have charged excessive prices for the urgent supply of 500,000 face masks to the SAPS in April 2020. The SAPS needed 9 million masks per month for its staff at the time. READ: WATCH | Digital Vibes | SIU to pursue more corruption suspects Tsutsumani sold its mask for more than R32 each after securing them for just R17 each from its supplier. The company however, denies the allegations of excessive pricing. The Competition Tribunal says it will now be taking a closer look at other suppliers in order to gauge prices.